00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:53.820
Let's turn now to a CBS News investigation.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:56.760
Military families have long complained about illnesses

00:09:56.760 --> 00:10:00.120
after they were exposed to water contaminated with carcinogenic

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:02.220
chemicals like benzene and dry cleaning liquids

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:05.010
at Camp Lejeune Military Base in North Carolina.

00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:08.170
To make matters worse, veterans who tried to get help

00:10:08.170 --> 00:10:11.430
are now describing a broken VA claims system.

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:14.190
Here's CBS's Catherine Herridge.

00:10:14.190 --> 00:10:17.130
I was a very healthy man until 67 years old.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:20.820
A lifelong aviator, Marine Corps veteran Mark Koutnor

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:24.150
thought he'd be working on his plane and taking to the skies

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:25.410
during retirement.

00:10:25.410 --> 00:10:29.490
But in 2017, Koutnor was diagnosed with prostate

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:31.260
and then pancreatic cancer.

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:33.750
Why did I have two cancer's back to back like this?

00:10:33.750 --> 00:10:37.590
As a young Marine, Koutnor has spent the summer of 1977

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:38.820
at Camp Lejeune.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:43.200
The government admits that between 1953 and 1987,

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:45.630
nearly a million veterans and civilians

00:10:45.630 --> 00:10:48.060
were potentially exposed to contaminated

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:51.240
drinking water at the North Carolina military base.

00:10:51.240 --> 00:10:54.360
How many doctors have blamed your cancer

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:56.880
on the contaminated water at Camp Lejeune?

00:10:56.880 --> 00:10:57.510
Seven.

00:10:57.510 --> 00:11:00.570
With letters from the country's leading cancer specialists,

00:11:00.570 --> 00:11:04.080
Koutnor filed a VA claim, connecting his cancers

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:05.880
to his time at Camp Lejeune.

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:07.650
It instantly just got denied.

00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:11.340
Based on your experience, is the VA system working?

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:12.330
No, not at all.

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:15.000
It's completely failing veterans.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.610
Mike Wishnie runs the Veterans Legal Services

00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:19.080
Clinic at Yale Law School.

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:21.840
His students filed a lawsuit in 2016,

00:11:21.840 --> 00:11:24.480
seeking more information about the doctors who

00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:28.650
review their claims, known as subject matter experts or SMEs.

00:11:28.650 --> 00:11:30.990
Not all of them appeared to have the qualifications

00:11:30.990 --> 00:11:32.160
for the job they were doing.

00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:35.040
According to documents obtained by CBS News,

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:38.730
the approval rate dropped from 25 to 5%

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:40.890
after they brought in these experts.

00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:43.980
The VA says the average approval rate is now

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:46.710
17%, though, their own data shows

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:49.230
it went as low as just 1%.

00:11:49.230 --> 00:11:51.840
They're saying it's deny, deny, deny until they die.

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:54.930
The VA denied Koutnor's claim on the basis

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:58.200
that their subject matter expert was more persuasive.

00:11:58.200 --> 00:12:00.810
They don't want to step up and do the right thing.

00:12:00.810 --> 00:12:04.110
Koutnor now is appealing and says it's not about the money.

00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:06.250
My appeal now is 18 months old.

00:12:06.250 --> 00:12:09.510
I'm hoping to hear before in my lifetime,

00:12:09.510 --> 00:12:11.670
but there's no guarantee.

00:12:11.670 --> 00:12:13.590
In a statement to CBS News, the VA

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:16.350
says it's committed to the processing of all claims

00:12:16.350 --> 00:12:20.310
to ensure priority veterans are served as timely and accurately

00:12:20.310 --> 00:12:21.210
as possible.

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:23.190
They told us the doctor in Mark's case

00:12:23.190 --> 00:12:25.500
has appropriate credentials and also

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.630
received four hours of additional training

00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:31.450
to evaluate contaminated water cases at Camp Lejeune.

00:12:31.450 --> 00:12:32.460
Norah.

00:12:32.460 --> 00:12:35.110
Catherine Herridge, with that important investigation,

00:12:35.110 --> 00:12:36.370
thank you.

00:12:36.370 --> 00:12:38.370
Let's turn now to Beijing and the Olympics,

00:12:38.370 --> 00:12:41.160
where the US men's hockey team had their gold medal

00:12:41.160 --> 00:12:44.220
dreams melt away, following a 3 to 2

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:46.050
quarterfinal loss to Slovakia.

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:49.050
Meanwhile, tonight, root for girl power, with the US women's

00:12:49.050 --> 00:12:53.550
hockey team once again going for gold against archrival Canada.

00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:58.070
CBS' Jamie Yuccas has a preview of the big game.

00:12:58.070 --> 00:13:00.770
This is the sixth time these teams have battled

00:13:00.770 --> 00:13:02.810
for gold in the Olympic finals.

00:13:02.810 --> 00:13:05.120
Canada has won three times.

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:08.030
Tonight, the Americans hope to even the score.

00:13:08.030 --> 00:13:10.910
We bring out the best level of competition from one another.

00:13:10.910 --> 00:13:13.490
We spent time with Hilary Knight and the rest of the team

00:13:13.490 --> 00:13:15.130
before they left for Beijing.

00:13:15.130 --> 00:13:17.450
We are in those jerseys.

00:13:17.450 --> 00:13:19.540
Hate is probably a word that comes up a lot.

00:13:19.540 --> 00:13:20.060
Hate?

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:22.970
Yeah, we hate one another, right?

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:26.900
These women are all about perseverance, many growing up

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:29.090
without leagues of their own.

00:13:29.090 --> 00:13:32.090
I grew up in a place where women didn't really

00:13:32.090 --> 00:13:33.360
play hockey at all.

00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:36.380
So I was a figure skater to start out.

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:38.540
I hated it so much.

00:13:38.540 --> 00:13:40.790
Abby Roque is the first Indigenous woman

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:42.770
to skate for Team USA Hockey.

00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:44.690
She's also a dual citizen.

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:46.860
Her dad is Canadian.

00:13:46.860 --> 00:13:49.820
He had to switch his hats and put on the USA cap.

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:51.460
I feel kind of bad for dad.

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:52.400
Yeah.

00:13:52.400 --> 00:13:55.370
He's switched sides, to the good side.

00:13:55.370 --> 00:13:58.370
These women say, they're not only shooting for gold.

00:13:58.370 --> 00:14:00.860
There's another goal.

00:14:00.860 --> 00:14:02.690
We're the women that are doing it,

00:14:02.690 --> 00:14:05.450
like we're in the trenches building something.

00:14:05.450 --> 00:14:10.910
Building a future, not just for themselves, but for the sport.

00:14:10.910 --> 00:14:14.000
If we can inspire and even be a spark in someone's dream,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.710
and we've done our job.

00:14:15.710 --> 00:14:17.900
And Jamie Yuccas joins us now from Beijing.

00:14:17.900 --> 00:14:20.120
And Jamie, they've already played each other

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:23.100
this Olympics, right?

00:14:23.100 --> 00:14:23.670
They did.

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:26.490
These two tangled eight days ago in round robin play.

00:14:26.490 --> 00:14:28.110
Canada did win that game.

00:14:28.110 --> 00:14:29.990
But now, the hardware is on the line, Norah,

00:14:29.990 --> 00:14:31.200
so it should be fun to watch.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:33.600
Because these two teams, I have to tell you,

00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:35.020
they hate each other.

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:38.520
But what we love is that every time these two meet,

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:42.060
little girls start participating in the sport more all

00:14:42.060 --> 00:14:42.820
around the world.

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:44.280
So that is a cool thing.

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:45.780
Yeah, a strong match-up.

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:47.790
Jamie Yuccas, thanks.

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:49.800
The Los Angeles Rams got the Hollywood ending

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:51.150
they wanted at the Super Bowl.

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:53.790
And today, they held the first championship victory parade

00:14:53.790 --> 00:14:55.590
in LA since 2014.

00:14:55.590 --> 00:14:57.960
The pandemic forced LA Lakers and the Dodgers

00:14:57.960 --> 00:14:59.820
to cancel parades in 2020.

00:14:59.820 --> 00:15:03.650
Quarterback Matthew Stafford, Super Bowl MVP, Cooper Kupp,

00:15:03.650 --> 00:15:05.400
and Aaron Donald, and the rest of the team

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:10.270
celebrated in a sea of Rams' blue and yellow.

00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:11.730
All right, still ahead on tonight's

00:15:11.730 --> 00:15:14.310
CBS Evening News, the investigation following

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:16.950
the fiery explosion of a truck carrying thousands

00:15:16.950 --> 00:15:20.280
of gallons of gasoline and a victory in court

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:21.660
for the family of Bob Saget.

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:24.900
Why records related to his death investigation

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:26.520
are not going to be released for now.

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:30.550
And why avocados will soon be in short supply.

00:15:30.550 --> 00:15:32.970
And if you can find them, it'll cost you.

00:15:32.970 --> 00:15:38.270


00:15:38.270 --> 00:15:40.000
Tonight, a Florida judge is temporarily

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.840
blocking the release of photos, video,

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:43.840
and other records connected to the investigation

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:45.790
and to the death of Bob Saget.

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:48.010
The actor and comedian's family sued

00:15:48.010 --> 00:15:50.260
a Florida Sheriff and a medical examiner's office

00:15:50.260 --> 00:15:51.520
to block the release.

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:54.910
The judge agreed it would cause them emotional distress.

00:15:54.910 --> 00:15:56.680
The medical examiner said last week

00:15:56.680 --> 00:16:00.310
that Saget suffered severe skull fractures, likely from a fall

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:02.890
or from hitting his head on the headboard of his bed,

00:16:02.890 --> 00:16:05.410
and ruled his death accidental.

00:16:05.410 --> 00:16:08.050
All right, tonight, officials in Rockville, Center in New York

00:16:08.050 --> 00:16:12.070
are investigating what led to the fiery crash of a tanker

00:16:12.070 --> 00:16:15.790
truck, holding more than 9,000 gallons of gasoline.

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:19.600
The truck crashed into a vacant building and burst into flames.

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:22.120
Burning fuel leaked into the sewer system,

00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:24.700
sending flames shooting out of manholes.

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:26.980
Power was cut to the hundreds of homes in the area

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:28.480
to prevent another fire.

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:30.400
The truck driver and three firefighters

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:32.420
are being treated for injuries.

00:16:32.420 --> 00:16:32.920
All right.

00:16:32.920 --> 00:16:34.510
Now, to this important story.

00:16:34.510 --> 00:16:38.320
If you love guacamole, you'll want to pay attention.

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:41.500
The US stopped all avocado imports from Mexico

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:44.800
until further notice, following a threat to an American safety

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:45.580
inspector.

00:16:45.580 --> 00:16:48.640
The threat comes amid escalating drug cartel violence

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:53.200
in the region, where nearly 90% of avocados imported to the US

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:53.920
come from.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:57.400
The disruption could lead to an avocado shortage

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:00.070
and, yes, a spike in prices.

00:17:00.070 --> 00:17:02.620


00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:04.630
Up next, an American quilt maker who

00:17:04.630 --> 00:17:07.300
is weaving her way into history and teaching it

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:09.670
at the same time.

00:17:09.670 --> 00:17:12.980
If you can't watch the CBS Evening News, you can listen.

00:17:12.980 --> 00:17:15.020
Subscribe wherever you get your podcasts.

00:17:15.020 --> 00:17:16.900
Sponsored by Principal Financial Group.

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:22.540


00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:25.600
Long ago, quilt-making took the leap from our grandmother's bed

00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:28.720
covering to the walls of art museums around the world.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:30.730
As part of Black History Month series,

00:17:30.730 --> 00:17:32.590
CBS's Maurice DuBois has the story

00:17:32.590 --> 00:17:35.230
of an artist who's making history and teaching

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:38.640
it one stitch at a time.

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:41.190
Bisa Butler's artwork has a way of stopping people

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:42.540
in their tracks.

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:43.500
Amazing, right?

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:44.400
Oh, my gosh.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:46.200
Her life-sized portraits look like they're

00:17:46.200 --> 00:17:49.160
from the strokes of a painter's brush.

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:52.670
But Butler is a quilt-maker, weaving fabrics of all kinds

00:17:52.670 --> 00:17:55.640
into celebrations of Black life in America.

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:58.340
I always want my portraits to be life-sized,

00:17:58.340 --> 00:18:01.550
to look the person in the eye, and to grab them.

00:18:01.550 --> 00:18:04.640
Butler says she is often inspired by historical photos

00:18:04.640 --> 00:18:08.540
like this one in 1940, a North Carolina family fleeing the Jim

00:18:08.540 --> 00:18:09.500
Crow South.

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:13.400
In seven months, she transformed their story onto fabric.

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:15.830
What about this photo jumped out at you?

00:18:15.830 --> 00:18:20.540
That this family was so unified in coming so far,

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:24.800
and that they were seeking better.

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:26.990
She learned to sew from her mother and grandmother

00:18:26.990 --> 00:18:29.300
and started out as a school art teacher.

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:32.390
Now, her work graces major magazine covers.

00:18:32.390 --> 00:18:34.610
Last year, she had her first solo show

00:18:34.610 --> 00:18:36.770
at the famed Art Institute of Chicago.

00:18:36.770 --> 00:18:37.820
I love the hair.

00:18:37.820 --> 00:18:39.110
I love the hair on these.

00:18:39.110 --> 00:18:42.590
Does it feel like you're filling in a gap in history that

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:44.180
was just left out?

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:45.350
Absolutely.

00:18:45.350 --> 00:18:46.070
Absolutely.

00:18:46.070 --> 00:18:48.320
I feel like our history has often

00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:53.090
been either concealed, deliberately erased,

00:18:53.090 --> 00:18:55.550
or ignored.

00:18:55.550 --> 00:18:58.610
It took Butler 11 months to create her most recent quilt,

00:18:58.610 --> 00:19:01.310
commissioned by the Smithsonian, depicting the Harlem

00:19:01.310 --> 00:19:03.650
Hellfighters and all Black infantry that

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:05.330
fought in World War I.

00:19:05.330 --> 00:19:09.350
They hoped that if they fought valiantly in Europe,

00:19:09.350 --> 00:19:10.910
that when they came back to the US,

00:19:10.910 --> 00:19:12.750
they would be treated differently.

00:19:12.750 --> 00:19:13.910
They were not.

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:16.700
A life mission, stitching together the African-American

00:19:16.700 --> 00:19:19.550
experience one portrait at a time

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:23.730
Maurice DuBois, CBS News, Newark, New Jersey.

00:19:23.730 --> 00:19:25.230
Absolutely stunning.

00:19:25.230 --> 00:19:27.880
We'll be right back.

